19. obtrectatores. Besides Calvus and Brutus, mentioned below, there were the Asinii, father and son, and also Caelius. These were all Atticists of the severer type, who considered the sulness and richness of Cicero's style turgidity and bombast, and pointed to the excessive attention which they alleged that he paid to rhythm as proving that he was really an Asianist in disguise. Cp. note on Quint. x. 1, 105.
